    body:`
<p>Three things this week, none of them small.</p>

<h3>The Fed Flipped</h3>
<p>Warsh's first meeting as chair held rates at 3.50 to 3.75%, no surprise there. The real surprise was the dot plot. <strong>Nine of eighteen officials now want a hike this year</strong>, six of those want two. Back in March the median call was a cut. Now it's a hike. Warsh didn't even submit his own dot, said he doesn't believe in the exercise, then just let the rest of the committee's hawkish swing do the talking for him. New chairs usually try to look tough out of the gate to prove they're serious. He went all in on that immediately. Market reacted exactly how you'd think: S&P down 0.6% that day, 2-year yield up 11bps.</p>

<h3>Peace Deal Signed, Already Wobbling</h3>
<p>The US and Iran signed a 14-point framework June 17. Iran agrees to never build a nuke, hands the enriched stockpile over for IAEA-supervised down-blending, and opens the Strait toll-free for 60 days. US dangles $300B for reconstruction if the rest of the deal holds. Four days later Iran said it closed the Strait again over Lebanon strikes. US Central Command says shipping is normal. Trump threatened the Iranian negotiators directly. Markets are pricing this as basically done. The actual situation says otherwise.</p>

<h3>SpaceX: Up 60%, Then Mostly Gone</h3>
<p>Priced at $135 on the 12th. Hit $217 four days later when they announced the Cursor acquisition. Down to $165 by the 22nd, third red day in a row. This is exactly what happens with a float that thin. I called this out in Alt Radar, just didn't think the round trip would happen this fast.</p>

<h3>The Numbers</h3>
<p>S&P at 7,472, down 0.4% Monday. Alphabet -5% on AI talent exit worries. Russell 2000 up ~21% YTD, miles ahead of the S&P. 10-year at 4.47%. 2026 PCE forecast revised up to 3.6% from 2.7%, which is the whole reason the dots moved.</p>

<h3>Monthly Pick Check-In</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>FTAI:</strong> nothing's changed. MRO demand doesn't care about Fed dots or Iran headlines. Still holding.</li>
<li><strong>COHR:</strong> same here. The Nvidia relationship and the 2028 backlog don't move because of anything that happened this week. Still holding.</li>
</ul>

<h3>Watching</h3>
<p>Whether the Strait closure is real or theater before the next round of talks. And whether Warsh's second presser confirms this was a one-time signal or the new normal.</p>`,
